🧠 Introduction

Conditional statements help programs make decisions based on conditions.

Control flow determines how the program executes step by step.

---

🔹 What is a Conditional Statement?

```text id="conditional_def"
A conditional statement executes different blocks of code based on whether a condition is True or False.
````

---

🎯 Why Conditional Statements Matter

✔ Decision making
✔ Dynamic programs
✔ User-based responses
✔ Core programming logic

-----------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------

🔀 What is Control Flow?

```text id="control_flow_def"
Control flow is the order in which program instructions are executed.
```

---

📌 Types of Conditional Statements

| Statement      | Purpose                            |
| -------------- | ---------------------------------- |
| `if`           | Execute block if condition is true |
| `if-else`      | Choose between two blocks          |
| `if-elif-else` | Multiple conditions                |
| Nested `if`    | Conditions inside conditions       |

---

🔹 1. if Statement

Executes code only if condition is true.

---

💻 Example

```python id="if_example"
age = 18

if age >= 18:
    print("Eligible to vote")
```

---

▶️ Output

```text id="if_output"
Eligible to vote
```

---

🔹 2. if-else Statement

Used when there are two possible outcomes.

---

💻 Example

```python id="if_else_example"
number = 5

if number % 2 == 0:
    print("Even Number")
else:
    print("Odd Number")
```

---

▶️ Output

```text id="if_else_output"
Odd Number
```

---

🔹 3. if-elif-else Statement

Used for multiple conditions.

---

💻 Example

```python id="elif_example"
marks = 75

if marks >= 90:
    print("Grade A")
elif marks >= 75:
    print("Grade B")
elif marks >= 50:
    print("Grade C")
else:
    print("Fail")
```

---

▶️ Output

```text id="elif_output"
Grade B
```

---

🔹 4. Nested if Statement

An `if` statement inside another `if`.

---

💻 Example

```python id="nested_if_example"
age = 20
has_id = True

if age >= 18:
    if has_id:
        print("Entry Allowed")
```

---

▶️ Output

```text id="nested_if_output"
Entry Allowed
```

---

⚖️ Comparison Operators in Conditions

| Operator | Meaning               |
| -------- | --------------------- |
| `==`     | Equal to              |
| `!=`     | Not equal             |
| `>`      | Greater than          |
| `<`      | Less than             |
| `>=`     | Greater than or equal |
| `<=`     | Less than or equal    |

---

🔗 Logical Operators

| Operator | Meaning              |
| -------- | -------------------- |
| `and`    | Both conditions true |
| `or`     | At least one true    |
| `not`    | Reverse condition    |

---

💻 Logical Operator Example

```python id="logical_condition_example"
age = 25
citizen = True

if age >= 18 and citizen:
    print("Eligible")
```

---

▶️ Output

```text id="logical_output"
Eligible
```

---

🧠 Truthy & Falsy Values

Python treats some values as `False`.

---

❌ Falsy Values

| Value   |
| ------- |
| `0`     |
| `False` |
| `None`  |
| `""`    |
| `[]`    |

---

💻 Example

```python id="truthy_example"
name = ""

if name:
    print("Name exists")
else:
    print("Empty String")
```

---

▶️ Output

```text id="truthy_output"
Empty String
```

---

🔄 Short-Hand if Statement

Python supports single-line conditions.

---

💻 Example

```python id="short_if_example"
age = 20

print("Adult") if age >= 18 else print("Minor")
```

